04801nam a22007455i 9781571138347DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815711383477 a10.1515/97815711383472doi  a(DE-B1597)675706  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPT405b.S737 2012 7aSOC0220002bisacsh04a830.9/0092222  aGN 1411qBSZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/42429:1 aStehle, Maria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGhetto Voices in Contemporary German Culture :bTextscapes, Filmscapes, Soundscapes /cMaria Stehle.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2012] 1bCamden House, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (220 p.) :b6 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in German Literature Linguistics and Culture ;v12500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Ghetto Discourses and German Mediascapes -- t1: Ghettos and Feridun Zaimoglu’s Textscapes of the 1990s -- t2: Ghetto Filmscapes and the Politics of the Ghetto Film -- t3: Ghetto Soundscapes: Performances of Nation, Gender, and Authenticity -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIlluminates tensions and transformations in today's Germany by examining literary, filmic, and musical treatments of the ghetto metaphor.Accounts of how Germany has changed since unification often portray the Berlin Republic as a new Germany that has left the Nazi past and Cold War division behind and entered the new millennium as a peaceful, worldly, and cautiously proud nation. Closer inspection, however, reveals tensions between such views and the realities of a country that continues to struggle with racism, provincialism, and fear of the perceived Other. Mainstream media foster such fears by describing violence in ghetto schools, failed integration, and the loss of society's core values. The city emerges as a key site not only of ethnic and political tension but of social change. Maria Stehle illuminates these tensions and transformations by following the metaphor of the ghetto in literary works from the 1990s by Feridun Zaimoglu, in German ghettocentric films from the late 1990s and the early twenty-first century, and in hip-hop and rap music of the same periods. In their representations of ghettos, authors, filmmakers, musicians, and performers redefine and challenge provincialism and nationalism and employ transcultural frameworks for their diverging political agendas. By contextualizing these discussions within social and political developments, this study illuminates the complexities that define Germany today for scholars and students across the disciplines of German, European,cultural, urban, and media studies. Maria Stehle is Assistant Professor of German at the University of Tennessee, Knoxville.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCities and towns in motion pictures. 0aGerman literaturey20th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aGermans. 0aInner cities in literature. 0aInner citieszGermany. 0aMass mediazGermany. 0aNational characteristics, German. 0aOther (Philosophy) in mass media. 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aGerman Literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aBerlin Republic.  aGerman culture.  acultural studies.  aghetto metaphor.  ahip-hop.  amedia studies.  aracism.  arap music.  asocial change.  aurban studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978157113834740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781571138347423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781571138347/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell 